# Integrating CodeSmith with the Main Application

To connect `src/codesmith` to your core application out of the box while keeping the deployment and preview logic intact—and to ensure it leverages your custom API keys and configured models per-agent—you need to follow two main steps:

1. **Update the [ModelResolver](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/src/core/shims/model-resolver.ts#35-90)** to fetch your specific agent models from [config/settings.json](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/config/settings.json) and API keys.
2. **Hook CodeSmith into the Chat Subsystem** ([app/routes/api.chat.ts](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/app/routes/api.chat.ts)) so that when the user queries the LLM, [CodeSmithExecutionService](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/src/core/codesmith/codesmith-execution.service.ts#13-114) intercepts the request and generates the output.

Here is what you need to do to achieve this.

---

## Step 1: Tell CodeSmith to use your Custom API Key and Models

Currently, [ModelResolver](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/src/core/shims/model-resolver.ts#35-90) in [src/core/shims/model-resolver.ts](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/src/core/shims/model-resolver.ts) falls back to `openai/gpt-4.1`. We need to override it so it fetches the model allocated to the specific agent ID from [config/settings.json](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/config/settings.json).

**Open [src/core/shims/model-resolver.ts](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/src/core/shims/model-resolver.ts)** and update the `ModelResolver.callModel` method to dynamically look up the model:

```typescript
import { generateText } from 'ai';
import { createOpenAI } from '@ai-sdk/openai';
import { AdminConfig } from './admin-config';
import { RuntimeEnv } from './runtime-env';

// ... (keep the same interfaces CallModelParams and CallModelResult)

export class ModelResolver {
    static async callModel(params: CallModelParams): Promise<CallModelResult> {
        // Automatically fetch your OPENROUTER API KEY (from config/admin.env via AdminConfig)
        const apiKey = AdminConfig.getOpenRouterApiKey(true);
        const baseURL = AdminConfig.getOpenRouterBaseUrl();

        // Check if there's a custom model mapping for this specific agent in `config/settings.json`
        const agentModels = AdminConfig.getCodeSmithAgentModels();
        const extractedAgentKey = params.agent_id.replace('codesmith:', ''); // e.g., 'codesmith:ceo:clarifier' -> 'ceo'
        const baseAgentRole = extractedAgentKey.split(':')[0];
        
        let modelName = params.preferred_model || agentModels[baseAgentRole] || 'openai/gpt-4.1';
        
        const maxTokens = params.max_tokens || 4000;
        const maxRetries = Math.max(1, RuntimeEnv.getNumber('CODESMITH_OPENROUTER_MAX_RETRIES', 3));
        const baseRetryDelayMs = Math.max(100, RuntimeEnv.getNumber('CODESMITH_OPENROUTER_RETRY_DELAY_MS', 1200));
        const maxRetryDelayMs = Math.max(baseRetryDelayMs, RuntimeEnv.getNumber('CODESMITH_OPENROUTER_RETRY_MAX_DELAY_MS', 8000));

        const openrouter = createOpenAI({
            baseURL,
            apiKey,
            // If you wish to use standard OpenAI, you can remove baseURL and just pass standard OpenAI apiKey.
        });

        // Continue with the execution...
        let attempt = 0;
        while (attempt < maxRetries) {
            try {
                const result = await generateText({
                    model: openrouter(modelName),
                    system: params.system_prompt || undefined,
                    prompt: params.prompt,
                    maxTokens,
                    temperature: params.model_config?.temperature ?? 0.2,
                });

                return {
                    response: result.text,
                    model_used: modelName,
                    tokens_used: result.usage?.totalTokens || 0,
                };
            } catch (error) {
                // Retry logic and error handling remains the same as your existing structure
                attempt += 1;
                const errorMessage = error instanceof Error ? error.message.toLowerCase() : String(error).toLowerCase();
                const status = Number((error as { status?: unknown; statusCode?: unknown } | null)?.status
                    || (error as { status?: unknown; statusCode?: unknown } | null)?.statusCode
                    || 0);
                const isOverloaded = status === 529 || errorMessage.includes(' 529') || errorMessage.includes('overload');

                if (!isOverloaded || attempt >= maxRetries) {
                    throw error;
                }
                const delayMs = Math.min(maxRetryDelayMs, baseRetryDelayMs * 2 ** (attempt - 1));
                await new Promise((resolve) => setTimeout(resolve, delayMs));
            }
        }

        throw new Error(`OpenRouter call failed after ${maxRetries} attempt(s)`);
    }
}
```

This guarantees that every agent in [CodeSmith](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/src/core/codesmith/agent-catalog.ts#57-58) leverages the exact model configured inside [config/settings.json](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/config/settings.json) under `codesmith_agent_models`.

---

## Step 2: Hook CodeSmith into your Core App Chat (StreamText)

Your app currently uses [app/routes/api.chat.ts](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/app/routes/api.chat.ts) and [streamText](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/src/core/codesmith/codesmith-orchestration.service.ts#338-360) to process natural language. To preserve deployment and previewing natively built into Bolt's default [streamText](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/src/core/codesmith/codesmith-orchestration.service.ts#338-360) mechanism, you will pipe the [CodeSmithExecutionService](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/src/core/codesmith/codesmith-execution.service.ts#13-114) result into the data stream.

**Open [app/routes/api.chat.ts](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/app/routes/api.chat.ts)** 

**1. Import CodeSmith Execution Services at the top of the file:**
```typescript
import { CodeSmithExecutionService } from '~/../src/core/codesmith/codesmith-execution.service';
```

**2. Inside `dataStream = createDataStream({ async execute(dataStream) { ... } })`, look for where [streamText](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/src/core/codesmith/codesmith-orchestration.service.ts#338-360) is called to generate a response.** If your app passes `chatMode: 'build'` or you specifically want it to intercept the prompt, add this check:

```typescript
        // ADD THIS CHECK BEFORE streamText():
        if (chatMode === 'build' && env?.CODESMITH_ENABLED === 'true') {
          // If CodeSmith is requested, dispatch to the CodeSmith subsystem
          dataStream.writeData({
            type: 'progress',
            label: 'codesmith-agent',
            status: 'in-progress',
            order: progressCounter++,
            message: 'CodeSmith is compiling the project...',
          } satisfies ProgressAnnotation);

          try {
            // Note: Replace "default_workspace" or "user_id" with your dynamic IDs if you manage them.
            const codesmithResult = await CodeSmithExecutionService.executeAgentTask(
              generateId(), 
              { agent_id: 'ceo', name: 'CEOAgent', type: 'planning', role: 'ceo', description: '', dependencies: [], base_estimated_cost: 0, timeout_ms: 300000, max_retries: 2, capabilities: [], permissions: [], max_concurrent_tasks: 2 }, // Base config
              {
                workspace_id: 'default_workspace',
                user_id: 'local_user',
                mode: 'turbo', // or 'ultimate', mapped to your settings.json modes
                query: totalMessageContent, // Pass the aggregated prompt
              }
            );

            // Mock an assistant response into the datastream based on CodeSmith's output
            // The CodeSmith system applies diffs manually, so we just acknowledge completion to the UI.
            dataStream.writeData({
               type: 'progress',
               label: 'codesmith-agent',
               status: 'complete',
               order: progressCounter++,
               message: 'CodeSmith orchestration complete.',
            } satisfies ProgressAnnotation);

            const encoder = new TextEncoder();
            dataStream.writeMessageAnnotation({
              type: 'chatSummary',
              summary: codesmithResult.summary,
              chatId: generateId(),
            } as ContextAnnotation);
            
            // Finish early since CodeSmith auto-modifies the workspace directly
            return;
            
          } catch (codesmithError) {
             logger.error('CodeSmith failed:', codesmithError);
             throw codesmithError;
          }
        }

        // --- Keep existing Bolt streamText logic below this! ---
        dataStream.writeData({
          type: 'progress',
          label: 'response',
          status: 'in-progress',
          order: progressCounter++,
          message: 'Generating Response',
        } satisfies ProgressAnnotation);

        const result = await streamText({ ... })
```

### Why this works:
1. **API keys and Custom Models:** [ModelResolver](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/src/core/shims/model-resolver.ts#35-90) will dynamically extract the agent ID (`ceo`, `builder`, `tester`) and pull the associated LLM configuration from [settings.json](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/config/settings.json) (e.g. `openai/gpt-4.1` or `anthropic/claude-opus-4.6:thinking`). By extracting `adminEnv.OPENROUTER_API_KEY`, your own API integration is guaranteed.
2. **Preserved Deployment & Previewing:** Because you are just intercepting the task execution inside `createDataStream()`, your client-side React code and WebContainers will still see standard `progress` stream annotations, allowing deployments, test runs, and preview UI logic to continue functioning out of the box. [CodeSmithExecutionService](file:///d:/Downloads/bolt.diy-main/bolt.diy-main/src/core/codesmith/codesmith-execution.service.ts#13-114) writes directly into your workspace which inherently triggers the exact same file-refresh pipelines the basic LLM engine does.
